[Event "Alapin Gambit - Ch 1: Accepted, 6...Be7 main line"]
[Site "Checkable"]
[White "Repertoire"]
[Black "Chapter 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 {The Alapin Gambit. White develops a piece and dares Black to grab e4. Across 281,609 Lichess blitz/rapid games White scores 52 percent from here, and the positions are far easier to play for White: every plan is the same attacking plan.} dxe4 {Taken in 61 percent of games - 77 percent at 2200+. The declines 3...Nf6 and 3...c5 are Chapters 5 and 6.} 4. Nd2 {More accurate than the popular immediate 4.f3, and Stockfish agrees (-0.4, its top choice). The knight is headed for f3, c4 or e5, and White keeps every option of regaining e4 or gambitting it properly.} Nf6 {Natural development, 66 percent of games. 4...f5, trying to keep the pawn, is Chapter 4.} 5. f3 {The gambit proper. White opens the f-file at the cost of a pawn: after the recapture on f3 every white piece flows toward the black king. Stockfish defends to -0.8 with perfect play, but humans never manage it - White scores 52-53 percent at every rating band from 1400 to 2500.} exf3 {80 percent of players accept. The engine's stubborn 5...Nd5 is covered in Chapter 3.} 6. Ngxf3 {The right recapture: the d2-knight keeps its routes to c4, e5 and e4.} Be7 {Black's most popular setup (32 percent). The alternatives 6...Bd6, 6...b6, 6...Bb4 and 6...Nd5 are Chapter 3.} 7. Bd3 {Aimed at h7. White's attack now plays itself: O-O, Qe1-h4, Ne5, Bg5, rooks to the half-open f-file.} O-O 8. O-O {Both sides castle short - but only one king will feel a breeze. The lift Qe1-h4 is coming.} b6 (8... Nbd7 9. Qe1 {The signature regrouping: the queen swings to h4. White scores 58 percent from this position.} c5 {The thematic French break, but it arrives too late: lines open while White's pieces are already pointed at the king. Stockfish +1.1.} (9... b6 10. Qh4 Bb7 (10... g6 {Stopping the queen's entry on h7 - but the dark squares pay the price.} 11. Ng5 h5 12. Nxe6 {The knight forks d8 and f8. And the defensive try 12...fxe6 fails to 13.Bxg6: Stockfish +2.7 with the king ripped open.}) 11. Ne5 {The octopus lands. Black is already busted on the engine: the f7/g6/h7 complex cannot be held forever.} g6 12. Bg5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Ne4 {The d2-knight joins the hunt via e4, eyeing f6 and d6.} Bxg5 15. Nxg5 h5 16. Be4 {+2.5. A pawn down, utterly winning: the dark squares around the king are ruined and every white piece participates. White scores 80 percent from here.}) (9... Re8 10. Qh4 Nf8 {Black has arranged the classical defensive setup - and Stockfish already shows +2.6, because f7 and h7 still cannot both be covered.} 11. Ng5 h5 12. Ndf3 {Threatening to win on h5: the engine line runs 12...N6h7 13.Bxh7+ Nxh7 14.Qxh5 with +2.8 and the attack rolling on.}) 10. Qh4 cxd4 (10... g6 11. Bg5 {+1.0, and White scores 78 percent: the pin is miserable to face with the dark squares this soft.}) 11. Bg5 h6 {Played in a third of games - and losing on the spot.} (11... g6 12. Rae1 {Calm: with the a1-rook joining, every white piece aims at e6 and f7. The engine continues 12...Nb6 13.Ne5 keeping +1.1.}) 12. Bxh6 {+4.7. After 12...gxh6 13.Qxh6 the threats of Ng5 and a rook lift decide immediately.}) (8... Nc6 9. c3 {Blunting ...Nb4 against the d3-bishop and shoring up d4. The c6-knight now bites on granite.} Nd5 (9... b6 10. Qe2 {With a knight ready to land on d5, the queen takes the e2 square instead: Rae1 and Ne5 come next, and White keeps full attacking flexibility.}) 10. Bf2 {The bishop steps out of the trade and keeps the dark-square grip.} Nf4 (10... Bf6 11. Qe1 {The lift proceeds regardless - +0.3 and a 70 percent practical score. White will follow with Qh4 or Ne4 hitting the f6-bishop.}) 11. Bc2 {Keeping the bishop pair trained on the kingside; g3 will evict the knight next. The engine calls it equal - the practical chances are all White's.}) 9. Qe1 {The signature lift. From h4 the queen will eye h7 and back every piece sacrifice on the kingside. White already scores 57 percent here.} Bb7 {Now Stockfish calls the position dead equal (+0.1) - the gambit pawn is fully compensated - and in practice White's score climbs to 58 percent.} 10. Qh4 Nbd7 (10... g6 11. Bg5 Nd5 {Trying to trade pieces - but the knight steps off the kingside at the worst moment.} (11... Nbd7 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Ne4 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 h5 16. Be4 {The same winning bind as in the main line: +2.5, dark squares gone, 80 percent score.}) 12. c4 {+2.9, and White scores a remarkable 94 percent: the knight has no decent square.} f6 13. Bh6 {Winning material: the f8-rook is dominated. Stockfish +3.0.}) 11. Ne5 {Clamping down on f7 and g6. Objectively balanced still - but Black must now find only-moves while White's play is effortless.} g6 {The most common defence (40 percent of games) - and the decisive mistake: Stockfish jumps to +1.7. The dark squares can never be repaired.} (11... Ne4 {The engine's defence: trade pieces at any cost.} 12. Qh3 {Keeping e6 and h7 in the crosshairs. Now the forcing line 12...Ndf6 13.Rf3 Nxd2 14.Rxf6 Ne4 15.Nxf7 Rxf7 16.Rxf7 ends +1.3 with Black's king permanently airy.} Ndf6 13. Rf3 {The rook lift: threatening to triple on the f-file or swing to h3.} Nxd2 14. Rxf6 {The exchange sacrifice that isn't: White regains everything by force.} Ne4 15. Nxf7 {The point. The knight grabs f7 with tempo on the queen via d8.} Rxf7 16. Rxf7 {+1.3. Material is level again but every black weakness remains: e6 hangs, the king is exposed, and Bc4 ideas pile up next.}) 12. Bg5 {+2.1. The e7-bishop is the only defender of the dark squares - so White trades it off or wins it.} Nxe5 (12... Nd5 13. Rxf7 {The half-open f-file cashes in: +3.3. The rook cannot be accepted comfortably, and f7 simply collapses.}) 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Ne4 {Heading for f6 or d6; note how the d2-knight has been a key attacker all game.} Bxg5 15. Nxg5 h5 16. Be4 {+2.5 and total domination for the pawn. This single line is the heart of the course: Bd3, Qe1-h4, Ne5, Bg5 - the same attack wins game after game at every level.} *

