1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 dxe4 4. Nd2 Nf6 5. f3 exf3 (5... Nd5 {The cold-blooded decline, and the higher rated the opponent, the likelier you face it: 3 percent at club level, 14 percent at 2200+. Black hits e3 and refuses to open the f-file.} 6. Qe2 {The repertoire recipe against every ...Nd5: protect nothing, prepare O-O-O, recapture on e3 with the queen.} Nxe3 (6... exf3 7. Ngxf3 Be7 (7... Nxe3 8. Qxe3 Nd7 9. O-O-O {The standard picture: develop with the long castle, then Ne5, h4, Bd3 or Bc4 as Black shows his hand. Engine -0.4: the honest price of the gambit, with all the play.}) 8. O-O-O O-O 9. Bf2 {Tucking the bishop away from ...Nxe3 once and for all. With opposite kings, White attacks with h4-h5 and g4; this position has scored 100 percent in the explorer sample.}) (6... Nc6 7. c3 {Solidifying d4 first.} exf3 8. Ngxf3 Nxe3 9. Qxe3 {Note Black's best here is the modest 9...Ne7 - after the natural 9...Be7 Stockfish already prefers White (+0.3): development and the open f-file outweigh the pawn.}) 7. Qxe3 exf3 8. Ngxf3 Be7 9. O-O-O {White is down a pawn with a -0.6 engine eval and a 52 percent practical score: the d-file rook, Ne5 and h4 give a full initiative. Both recapture orders land in this same position - learn it once.}) 6. Ngxf3 Bd6 {Second most popular (20 percent): more active than e7 - but the bishop abandons the kingside dark squares, and several traps below show why that matters.} (6... b6 7. Ne5 {Immediately exploiting the slow setup.} Bb7 8. Bb5+ {Forcing the block:} c6 9. Bd3 {and the b7-bishop now stares at its own c6-pawn. White has gained the e5-outpost and a tempo-free attack; 73 percent score from here.}) (6... Bb4 {A club-player favourite - 12 percent of games at 1400-1600 - and one of the best-scoring positions in the whole course for White: 64 percent.} 7. c3 {Putting the question immediately.} Be7 (7... Ba5 {Trying to keep the pin that no longer exists.} 8. Nc4 {+1.2. Hitting the bishop again: after 8...c5 9.Qa4+ Nc6 10.Nxa5 White simply wins the bishop pair and keeps the initiative.}) 8. Bd3 {The bishop returned home at the cost of two tempi - White has a free version of the main attack: O-O, Qe1-h4, Ne5. (60 percent score.)}) (6... Nc6 {Blocking the c-pawn to develop fast.} 7. Bd3 {Develop and ask the knight what it is doing: c3 next blunts it, and the standard O-O, Qe1-h4 machinery follows unchanged. Engine -0.6, White 55 percent in practice.}) (6... Nd5 7. Qe2 {The same medicine as always against ...Nd5.} Nxe3 (7... Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. Bf2 {Sidestep, castle long, attack. Black's setup makes no real threat.}) 8. Qxe3 Be7 9. O-O-O {Full compensation in practice: Ne5, Bd3 or Bc4, h4. White scores 52 percent; the engine's -0.5 never tells in human games.}) 7. Bd3 O-O (7... b6 8. O-O Bb7 9. Qe1 Nbd7 (9... O-O {Castling straight into it - with the bishop on d6 this is already lost.} 10. Qh4 {+2.7. The difference from the 6...Be7 lines: there is no ...Bxg5 defence. The engine line 10...Nbd7 11.Bg5 h6 12.Bxh6 crashes through at once.}) 10. Rd1 {The a1-rook supports d4 and x-rays the d6-bishop. White continues Qh4 and Ne5/Bg5 at leisure.}) (7... Nc6 8. O-O O-O (8... Bd7 9. c3 {Quiet consolidation: d4 is safe, so Qe1-h4 and Ne5 follow. Black's pieces step on each other.}) 9. c3 e5 {Black's cleanest equalising try in the 6...Bd6 complex.} (9... Re8 {Abandoning f7 with the f-file loaded - immediately decisive.} 10. Ng5 {+4.8. The threats on f7 and h7 cannot both be met: the engine gives 10...Bd7 11.Rxf6 Qxf6 12.Bxh7+ Kf8 13.Qh5 with a mating attack.}) 10. Ng5 {Keeping the pieces on and asking about f7 and h7 before Black consolidates. Objectively balanced - practically uncomfortable: 10...exd4 runs into Qh5-ideas, hence Black's score here stays modest.}) 8. Qe2 {Against the d6-setup the queen prefers e2: White keeps both castling options and the e-file. Watch how often O-O-O appears below.} b6 (8... Nbd7 9. O-O-O c5 10. Rhf1 {Full mobilisation before any commitment: from here White scores 71 percent - sacrifices on f6/f7 and the g4-g5 push are both in the air.}) (8... Nc6 9. c3 e5 {Again the freeing break - and again playable for Black.} 10. dxe5 {Simplest. After 10...Nxe5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 White continues O-O-O with quick rook pressure; the position is balanced, so play it with energy - the structure and lead in development still favour the better-prepared side.}) 9. O-O-O Bb7 10. Bg5 {Opposite kings, pin on f6, h4 next; the engine calls it equal and the score sheet says 61 percent for White. The gambit in its purest practical form.} *

