1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 dxe4 4. Nd2 f5 {The greedy try, 29 percent of games: Black keeps e4 at the price of weakening e6 and the a2-g8 diagonal - exactly where White's pieces want to go. From here the gambit is objectively sound: Stockfish reads equal or better for White everywhere.} 5. f3 {Insist. Either the f-file opens anyway or e4 falls.} exf3 {78 percent take again.} (5... Nf6 6. fxe4 fxe4 (6... Nxe4 {Played in a third of low-rated games - and refuted on the spot.} 7. Nxe4 fxe4 8. Qh5+ {The punishment for ...f5 in one move.} g6 9. Qe5 {Forking h8 and e4.} Rg8 10. Qxe4 {Material is level again, and compare the kings. Stockfish +0.8-+1.9; in practice White scores 59 percent and rising.} Nc6 (10... Bg7 {Naturally developing - and losing more: e6 cannot be defended.} 11. Bc4 {+3.6. The e6-pawn falls with the black king still in the centre.}) 11. Bc4 {+1.9. Pressure on e6 with the king stuck: White develops with threats on every move.}) 7. c3 {Solid: White will develop, castle and collect e4 at leisure - it cannot run away.} Bd6 (7... b6 8. Nh3 {+1.0. The knight reroutes via f4 or g5 straight at the weakened e6-pawn.}) 8. Bg5 {The annoying pin: 8...h6 9.Bxf6 Qxf6 and with the f5/e4 pawns loose and e6 soft, White regains everything with interest.}) 6. Ngxf3 {Everything from the accepted gambit, for free: f-file, development lead - and now e6 is weak too.} Nf6 7. Bc4 {The bishop switches diagonals to hit the new weakness. This is the structural difference from Chapters 1-3: e6 is the target now.} Bd6 (7... Nc6 {Stockfish's preference: cover e5 and fight for the centre.} 8. Qe2 Bd6 9. O-O-O {The full setup: pressure on e6 and the d-file, Bg5 and Rhe1 to come. White's score: 53 percent with all the fun.}) (7... c6 {Securing d5 - but blocking the queenside and ignoring development; a typical club mistake (10 percent of games).} 8. Qe2 Nd5 9. Bxd5 {Giving up the proud bishop to fix Black with a permanent weakness: after 9...cxd5 the e6-pawn is backward on a half-open file forever. Stockfish +1.3.}) 8. Qe2 O-O 9. O-O-O {Opposite kings with e6 in the crosshairs.} c6 (9... Nc6 10. Bg5 Re8 {Defending e6 laterally - too slow.} 11. c3 {+1.2, and a 100 percent score in the sample: White simply continues Ne5, h4 and Rhf1 while Black's counterplay never arrives.}) 10. Bg5 {+0.5 and a 66 percent practical score: the pin, Ne5, and h4 arrive while the e6-pawn ties Black down for the rest of the game.} *

