1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 Nf6 {Declining (19 percent of games) - and walking into a French Advance where White has the rare luxury of Be3 played for free. Stockfish: +0.7.} 4. e5 Nfd7 (4... Ne4 {The howler - yet it appears in 18 percent of games at 1400-1600. The knight has no support and no retreat.} 5. f3 {+3.3. Every knight move now loses material.} Ng5 (5... Qh4+ {The tricky try, beloved at higher bands - it loses a full piece to one precise sequence.} 6. g3 Nxg3 7. Bf2 {The skewer: the g3-knight is pinned against its own queen by the f2-bishop.} Nc6 (7... Qg5 8. hxg3 {+4.3. The h-pawn collects the knight; White is a piece up with open lines.}) (7... Bb4+ 8. c3 {Blocking with tempo. The knight on g3 still cannot move, and after the bishop retreats White harvests it at leisure. +3.7.}) 8. c3 {The key finesse (+3.5): deny ...Bb4+ and ...Qb4+ counterplay first. The knight cannot be saved - the engine line runs 8...Qh6 9.Bxg3 with a clean extra piece.}) 6. h4 {+4.2. The hunt: the knight is lost on every reply.} Nxf3+ {The desperado - knight takes pawn, but that is all it gets.} (6... Be7 7. hxg5 Bxg5 8. Bxg5 Qxg5 9. Qd2 {Consolidating a piece up: 9...Qg3+ 10.Kd1 and the checks run dry immediately. +4.3.}) (6... Ne4 7. fxe4 dxe4 8. Nc3 {+5.0. A whole piece for a pawn, and even the e4-pawn falls next.}) 7. Nxf3 Nc6 8. c3 {+4.7. A clean piece up: keep the centre, develop, win. White converts this 83 percent of the time.}) 5. f4 {The Advance French, improved: Be3 already defends d4, so Black's entire ...Qb6 counterplay system misfires.} c5 6. c3 Nc6 (6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {Trading the check for nothing.} 8. Nd2 {The modest block scores 82 percent here: the pin has no follow-up, and a3 plus Bd3 will collect tempi against the bishop.}) (6... Qb6 7. Qd2 Nc6 (7... cxd4 8. cxd4 {After 8...Bb4 9.Nc3 we transpose to the main line below - one repertoire, many move orders.}) 8. Nf3 {Transposing to the main line: ...Qb6 was answered by Qd2 and nothing in Black's setup works better for it.}) 7. Nf3 Qb6 {The standard French recipe: pile on d4 and b2. Here it earns Black a worse version of every known structure - d4 is overprotected.} (7... cxd4 8. cxd4 {The same position-type: ...Bb4+ is met by Nc3 or Nd2, ...Qb6 by Qd2. Stockfish +0.6-+1.1 everywhere.}) (7... Be7 8. Bd3 {Simple development: O-O next, then the standard kingside expansion with the f5-break always in reserve. +1.0.}) 8. Qd2 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bb4 {Pinning - the engine's main line.} (9... Be7 10. Nc3 {+1.5: compare any normal Advance French - White is two tempi up.}) 10. Nc3 O-O (10... Qa5 11. Bd3 Nb6 12. O-O {+0.8. The queenside demonstration achieved nothing; White's kingside majority and space tell. 59 percent score.}) 11. Bd3 f6 {The thematic counter-break - and here it backfires spectacularly.} 12. O-O {+2.2, with a 69 percent score. The point: after ...fxe5 fxe5 the f-file belongs to White, Ng5 and Bxh7 motifs abound, and e6 hangs in many lines. Everything Black wants to do helps White.} *

