1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 c5 {The French reflex - already imprecise here (Stockfish +0.9), and the source of more blunders than any other move: it appears in 11 percent of club games.} 4. dxc5 {The e3-bishop now guards c5 - a fact Black misses with astonishing frequency.} Qa5+ {The most cunning try (26 percent): Black gives a check expecting to win c5 next move.} (4... Bxc5 {11 percent of games, instantly losing a piece: the e3-bishop was watching.} 5. Bxc5 Qa5+ {The follow-up everyone intends: fork the king and bishop.} (5... Ne7 6. exd5 {A piece up with more coming; just develop and convert. +4.8.}) (5... Nc6 6. exd5 exd5 7. Bb5 {Piece up, pin on, d5 falling. +4.9.}) (5... dxe4 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Ne2 {Queens off, piece up, +5.4. The technique phase starts immediately.}) 6. b4 {The cold shower: one pawn move blocks the check and defends the bishop. Note 6...Qxb4+ fails to 7.Bxb4 - c5 covers b4.} Qc7 (6... Qa4 7. Nc3 {Hitting the queen again; +6.8 as Black's queen wanders alone while White develops with threats every move.}) (6... Qd8 7. exd5 {Best defence, hopeless position: +5.1 and 7...exd5 8.Nf3 next just develops up a piece.}) 7. exd5 {+5.0. Opening more lines while a piece up; 7...exd5 8.Nf3 and Black has nothing for it.}) (4... Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 {+1.2: the classic anti-isolani setup - pin the knight, pressure d5, keep the extra c5-pawn as long as it is convenient. White scores 54 percent and climbing with every accurate move.}) (4... Nf6 {Objectively Black's best: develop first, regain pawns later. Note it is chosen by 25 percent of 2200+ players and only 7 percent at club level.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 (5... Nxe4 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. Qxd8+ {+1.5. After 7...Kxd8 White keeps the extra c5-pawn in a queenless position with the safer king - a risk-free endgame grind that scores 57 percent.}) (5... Bxc5 {Even here the bishop cannot take.} 6. Bxc5 {+5.1: and if 6...Qa5 to fork, then 7.Qd4 holds c5 and everything else. A piece is a piece.}) 6. exd5 exd5 (6... Nxd5 7. Nxd5 {+2.2. After either recapture on d5 White consolidates the extra c5-pawn - for instance 7...Qxd5 8.Qxd5 exd5 and White is simply a sound pawn up.}) 7. Bb5 {+1.4: maximum pressure on d5 while Black is still proving compensation for one pawn.}) (4... dxe4 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nc3 {+1.4. A queenless middlegame where only White has threats: the king on d8 is a target down the d-file.} f5 {Trying to hold e4.} (6... Nf6 7. O-O-O+ {The point of having played Be3: long castling arrives with check. White regains e4 at leisure or keeps pressing the pinned-down king. +1.5.}) 7. O-O-O+ {+2.4. The check costs Black the right to coordinate: 7...Bd7 8.g4 or 7...Ke8 8.Nb5 - White's initiative plays itself at 58 percent.}) 5. Nc3 {Blocking with development. Now watch what happens to the players who grab c5.} Bxc5 {Here is the most instructive statistic in the course: 92 percent of all players - and even 71 percent of 2200+ players - take the pawn, certain that the queen on a5 protects the bishop.} (5... Nf6 {The engine's recommendation: keep developing.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 (6... Bxc5 {Still wrong, for the same beautiful reason:} 7. Bb5+ {+3.5. The check interposes on the fifth rank, severing the a5-queen's defence of c5 - next move White takes the bishop for free.}) (6... exd5 7. Bb5+ {+2.4: same geometry - block the fifth rank with check, then collect. Both 7...Bd7 and 7...Nc6 leave White a clean pawn up with the initiative after the c5-bishop falls or is traded favourably.}) 7. Bd2 {The precise move: break the a5-e1 pin with tempo. White keeps the extra c5-pawn; Stockfish +0.6 and a 60 percent practical score.}) (5... dxe4 {Grabbing a different pawn - now the queen gets harassed.} 6. a3 {Quiet and deadly: b4 comes with tempo, and e4 falls later.} Nf6 (6... Bxc5 7. Bb5+ {+4.5. The fifth-rank check once more - by now you know the geometry.}) (6... f5 {Holding e4 at all costs.} 7. b4 {+3.4. The queen is pushed around the board while White opens lines: 7...Qd8 8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.O-O-O+ or 7...Qc7 8.Nb5 - either way the initiative is overwhelming.}) 7. b4 {+1.8. After 7...Qc7 8.Nxe4 White has restored material with a big lead in development - the c5-pawn even survives a while.}) 6. Bb5+ {The move that makes this whole chapter worth learning. The check lands ON THE FIFTH RANK: the b5-bishop physically cuts the a5-queen's defence of c5. Whatever blocks the check, 7.Bxc5 wins a clean piece - and ...Qxc5 is literally illegal.} Bd7 (6... Nc6 7. Bxc5 {+5.2 - even better than the main trap: the c6-knight is pinned to the king, so Black cannot even fight back in the centre. The bishop on c5 is untouchable; White is a piece up.}) 7. Bxc5 {+3.6, winning a piece: the queen still cannot take c5 because b5 blocks the fifth rank. The engine's best for Black is 7...Bxb5 8.Qd4 - hitting g7 and consolidating - when 8...Nf6 9.exd5 keeps everything. White converts this position 61 percent of the time even at club level, and it should be 100.} *
